Are World Happiness and Suicide Linked?¶

Data Used In This Project¶

World Happiness Index
https://www.kaggle.com/mathurinache/world-happiness-report
(2015-2020) 2015.csv - 2020.csv

Suicide Rates
https://www.kaggle.com/szamil/who-suicide-statistics
(1979-2017) who_suicide_stastistics.csv

Hypotheses¶

  • Countries with a higher happiness index will have lower sucide rates and countries with s lower hapiness index will have higher suicide rates

                          'Trust (Government Corruption)', 'Generosity')]
sub2016 = whi_2016.loc[:,('Country', 'Happiness Score', 'Economy (GDP per Capita)', 'Family', 'Health (Life Expectancy)', 'Freedom',\
                          'Trust (Government Corruption)', 'Generosity')]
sub2017 = whi_2017.loc[:,('Country', 'Happiness.Score', 'Economy..GDP.per.Capita.', 'Family', 'Health..Life.Expectancy.', 'Freedom',\
                          'Trust..Government.Corruption.', 'Generosity')]
sub2018 = whi_2018.loc[:,('Country or region', 'Score', 'GDP per capita', 'Social support', 'Healthy life expectancy', 'Freedom to make life choices',\
                          'Perceptions of corruption', 'Generosity')]

## Rename columns so they all match
colnames = ['Country', 'Happiness', 'GDP', 'Support', 'Life_Expt', 'Freedom', 'Corruption', 'Generosity']

sub2016.columns = colnames
sub2017.columns = colnames
sub2018.columns = colnames

## Add Year column
sub2015["Year"] = 2015
sub2016["Year"] = 2016
sub2017["Year"] = 2017
sub2018["Year"] = 2018

## Check order of colnames and join together
print(sub2015.columns)
print(sub2016.columns)
print(sub2017.columns)
print(sub2018.columns)

Data Wrangling Suicide Dataset¶

Load suicide dataset, filter for years 2015 - 2016, remove NAs

In [ ]:
suicide = pd.read_csv("RawData/who_suicide_statistics.csv")
suicide["year"].max()

## filter for years 2015-2016
suicide_sub = suicide[suicide["year"] >= 2015]

## remove NAs: suicides_no and population both have NAs
suicide_sub.isnull().any()
suicide_na = suicide_sub[suicide_sub["suicides_no"].notna() & suicide_sub["population"].notna()]
suicide_na.isnull().any()

## filter happiness for years 2015 & 2016
happiness_sub = happiness[(happiness["Year"] == 2015) | (happiness["Year"] == 2016)]
happiness_sub["Year"].unique()
happiness_sub.isna().any() ## No NAs

Rename countries that are shared but not named the same between dataframes

In [ ]:
## Find countries with the same names in both suicide and happiness index datasets
sharedCountries = np.intersect1d(suicide_na["country"].unique(), happiness_sub["Country"].unique())

## Check other countries for name variences
print("Suicide DF\n")
for each in list(suicide_na["country"].unique()):
    if each not in sharedCountries:
        print(each)
        
print("\nHappiness DF\n")
for each in list(happiness_sub["Country"].unique()):
    if each not in sharedCountries:
        print(each)

changenames = {'Republic of Korea': 'South Korea', 'Hong Kong SAR': 'Hong Kong', 'United States of America':'United States', 'Republic of Moldova':'Moldova',\
               'Iran (Islamic Rep of)':'Iran', 'Russian Federation': 'Russia'}

suicide_na.loc[:,"country"] = suicide_na.loc[:,"country"].replace(changenames)
suicide_na["country"].unique()

Combine suicide and world happiness datasets by year and country

In [22]:
happiness_suicide = pd.merge(suicide_na, happiness_sub, how = "inner", left_on = ["country","year"], right_on = ["Country","Year"])
happiness_suicide = happiness_suicide[['country', 'year', 'sex', 'age', 'suicides_no', 'population', 'Happiness', 'GDP', 'Support',\
                                       'Life_Expt', 'Freedom', 'Corruption', 'Generosity']]

## Save dataframe to use later
happiness_suicide.to_csv("happiness_suicide.csv", sep= ",")

  • South Korea highest at 140.74 suicides per 100,000 people.
  • Ages are higher with most in 75+ category, second largest group is 55-74 years.
  • A lot of slavic countries in list of high outliers
  • Low outliers att 150 counts for age groups, no trend with age here
  • US in list of low outliers
In [46]:
suicide_iqr = iqr(happiness_suicide['suicides_per100k'])
print('IQR: ', suicide_iqr)

lower_thres = np.quantile(happiness_suicide['suicides_per100k'], 0.25) - 1.5 * suicide_iqr
upper_thres = np.quantile(happiness_suicide['suicides_per100k'], 0.75) + 1.5 * suicide_iqr

## filter for upper and lower outliers
highest_outliers = happiness_suicide[happiness_suicide['suicides_per100k'] > upper_thres]
lowest_outliers = happiness_suicide[happiness_suicide['suicides_per100k'] < lower_thres] ## Empty df; no low outliers

print(highest_outliers['country'].unique())
print(highest_outliers['age'].value_counts())

Muliple Regression¶

Can suicides per 100,000 people be predicted by happiness index?

Note: I used all available data to explore, therefore should not use same data split into test/training datasets. Therefore I will not test my model.

In [23]:
## Try happiness^2 first as parabolic curve that could fit data would be y=-x^2
happiness_suicide['Happiness2'] = happiness_suicide['Happiness']**2
model = smf.ols('suicides_per100k ~ Happiness + Happiness2', data=happiness_suicide)
results = model.fit()
results.params
Out[23]:
Intercept    -55.295997
Happiness     22.455385
Happiness2    -1.840828
dtype: float64
In [29]:
## Generate predictions to plot
df = pd.DataFrame()
df['Happiness'] = np.linspace(0,12)
df['Happiness2'] = df['Happiness']**2
predictions = results.predict(df)

## Plot model
happy_jittered = happiness_suicide['Happiness'] + np.random.normal(0, 2, size=len(happiness_suicide))
suicides = happiness_suicide['suicides_per100k']
plt.plot(df['Happiness'], predictions, label='Model')
plt.plot(happy_jittered, suicides, 'o', alpha=0.3)
plt.ylabel('Suicides per 100k people')
plt.ylim([0, 150])
plt.xlabel('Happiness Index')
plt.title('Happiness vs Suicides, Line of Best Fit: Happiness Only')
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 10, "figure.figsize": (10,10)})
plt.show()

Something else likely contributes to suicide prediction. Line of best fit seems low. Suicide rate definitly increases with age, so add age to multiple regression.

In [49]:
model = smf.ols('suicides_per100k ~ C(age) + Happiness + Happiness2', data=happiness_suicide)
results = model.fit()
results.params

## Generate predictions to plot
df = pd.DataFrame()
df['Happiness'] = np.linspace(0,12)
df['Happiness2'] = df['Happiness']**2
df['age'] = '15-24 years' ## Parabola moves up with age input here, 75+ is the highest
predictions_15 = results.predict(df)
df['age'] = '25-34 years'
predictions_25 = results.predict(df)
df['age'] = '35-54 years'
predictions_35 = results.predict(df)
df['age'] = '55-74 years'
predictions_55 = results.predict(df)
df['age'] = '75+ years'
predictions_75 = results.predict(df)

## Plot model
happy_jittered = happiness_suicide['Happiness'] + np.random.normal(0, 2, size=len(happiness_suicide))
suicides = happiness_suicide['suicides_per100k']
plt.plot(df['Happiness'], predictions_15, label='Age: 15-24 years', color ='red')
plt.plot(df['Happiness'], predictions_25, label='Age: 25-34 years', color ='blue')
plt.plot(df['Happiness'], predictions_35, label='Age: 35-54 years', color ='black')
plt.plot(df['Happiness'], predictions_55, label='Age: 55-74 years', color ='orange')
plt.plot(df['Happiness'], predictions_75, label='Age: 75+ years', color ='darkgreen')
plt.plot(happy_jittered, suicides, 'o', alpha=0.3)
plt.ylabel('Suicides per 100k people')
plt.ylim([0, 150])
plt.xlabel('Happiness Index')
plt.title('Happiness vs Suicides, Line of Best Fit: Happiness + Age')
plt.legend(loc="upper right")
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 10, "figure.figsize": (10,10)})
plt.show()

Conclusion: Age and Happiness Index Can Predict Suicide Rates¶

My hypothesis failed!Countries with lower happiness do not have higher suicide rates, rather countries with a happiness index around the average (6) have the highest suicide rates. Suicide rates clearly increase with age.
